own saver/loader. I haven't really looked at CNKI myself, tho maybe
the author can offer you insight on how to combine the files. Perhaps
cludging could be used.
 
> 2)   What is a chunki table ? how create this file ? can i use it for made
> transparency effect with shape ?

Did you read the documentation?

There are either 1 dimensional or 2 dimensional tables. In Mildred
these are referred to as MSimpleReMapMode and MReMapMode.

A 1 dimensional simple-remap table is just a sort of array of 256
bytes. Each byte in the array represents a colour. The value you store
there is the value that a colour will be changed to. The First byte at
offset 0 might be changed to 243, the second byte at offset 1 might
hold 15 - causing all pixels of 0 to be changed to 243 and all colours
of 1 to be canged to 15.

A one dimensional remap doesn't take any notice of the colours of your
shape - only the cookie shape.

A 2 dimensional remap table is an array of 256x256 bytes. One
dimension of the table represents the colours of your sprite and the
other dimension represents the colours of the destination. When the
remap is taking place, a pixel from the source and a pixel from the
destination are taken and placed alongside each other to give the
index in the matrix/array. The value found at that position in the
array is what will then be written to the destination.

There is an example of computing single and two dimensional tables.
Erm, Remap.lha? You can calculate it in different ways but to, for
example, make your shapes 50% transparent you have to do quite a bit
of work.

This is a piece of code to compute a 2 dimensional transparency table:

Dim R(256),G(256),B(256) ; This array is just for speed
PaletteInfo 0
For c=0 To 255
  R(c)=AGAPalRed(c)
  G(c)=AGAPalGreen(c)
  B(c)=AGAPalBlue(c)
Next c
TP.l=MTablePtr ; Base address of the 2 dimensional table/array
For SourceColour=0 To 255
  For DestColour=0 To 255
	Offset.l=(SourceColour LSL 8)+DestColour ; Offset in the array
R0=(R(SourceColour)+R(DestColour)) LSR 1 ; 50% merge source&dest
G0=(G(SourceColour)+G(DestColour)) LSR 1 ; 50% merge source&dest
B0=(B(SourceColour)+B(DestColour)) LSR 1 ; 50% merge source&dest
;R0=Min((R(SourceColour)+R(DestColour)),255)
;G0=Min((G(SourceColour)+G(DestColour)),255) ; Alternative for a
;B0=Min((B(SourceColour)+B(DestColour)),255) ; `minimum' operation
;R0=R(DestColour)*0.8
;G0=G(DestColour)*0.8 ; Alternative for an 80% shadow operation
;B0=B(DestColour)*0.8
	Best=0
	BestTotal.l=$0FFFFFFF
	For TestColour=0 To 255 ; Find the closest matching colour from
	  R1=R(TestColour)      ; your available palette
	  G1=G(TestColour) ; Shape colour
	  B1=B(TestColour)
	  Total.l=((R0-R1)*(R0-R1))+((G0-G1)*(G0-G1))+((B0-B1)*(B0-B1))
	  If Abs(Total)<BestTotal
		Best=TestColour
		BestTotal=Abs(Total)
	  EndIf
	Next TestColour
	Poke.b TP+Offset,Best
  Next DestColour
Next SourceColour

; You may want to save the table to a file and load it in because
; realtime computation takes a long time in a game or whatever

You may notice that you have to have set up your palette first of all
because a transparency effect is rather dependent on the palette
colours which are available and their order. A 50% merge simple
combines the colour of the source pixel with the colour of the
destination pixel and the works out what colour, from your available
palette, is the closest representation of that. When it has been found
the colour to use is put into that location in the table. And because
the source and dest can both have 256 colours, there are generally
256*256 combinations to check.. and for each of those 256 colours to
search. 

Note however that Mildred is coded so that if your source shape
doesn't use 256 colours, you can reduce the size of the table. But
this means the colours used should be in the LOWER end of the palette,
colours 0 upwards. Like, if you only used colours 0..64, then your
array only needs to be 256*64 in size.

It may take nearly a minute to compute a 256x256 array, so you should
work it out beforehand and load it in.

Then you simply use MReMapMode with one of the blits, having loaded in
the table data or computed it into a mildred Table object (currently
used).. . and away you blit. The source and dest values will be used
as an index into the array to call up the colour to plot to the
destination.

A one dimensional table is similar to work out but simpler. It only
has one dimension for a start.

Someone was working on coding a table generator for Mildred to make
things easier... who was that? Loki? Get that thing released, whoever
it is!

Note also that you can use MAddMode to do some transparency type
effects. For example, if you SORT your palette into order of
brightness and set MInk to 1 and use something like MBlitMode
MAddMode, and then MBlit your shape, the effect will be to lighten or
darken (depending on the order you sorted) the background in the shape
of your shape. And this is also faster than MSimpleReMap mode (one of
the main reasons I coded it). To render with even more
lightness/darkness you just change the MInk number. I'm not sure but I
think that the addition which takes places is a signed byte, so you
can use values -128 to 127 ... but of course, as a full byte this is
a number from 0 to 255. Hense MAddMode is the same thing as
MSubtractMode, if there was one. All subtraction is addition, you
know! :D

So anyway, you have the option of a full 2 dimensional combination of
source and dest using MReMapMode, a single dimension alteration to the
destination using the source's shape (cookie, in fact), or a
`tableless' change using MAddMode for simple effects. It may not be
desirable to sort your palette, or if you do it may not work how you
intended if you dont have a good even spread of colour, ie, certain
pixels may take on red green or blue tinges. Most people know what a
sorted palette looks like, roughly going from dark to light or vice
versa will all sorts of `fluctuations' along the way. But for some
purposes it is fine.

Your alternative is to use an interleaving. If set every OTHER colour
to what you want, and use in your game (making it kind of a 128-colour
engine)... and you set the remaining inbetween colours to the same but
with a slight variation - brighter, darker, a colour tint, then you
can use MInk 1 and MAddMode to do a simple and quick uniform
transparency effect, which might be all you want for a simple shadow
or a light or such, unless you want graduated lights, softshadows, etc
for which you need to use the shape's data and a two dimensional array
with MReMapMode.

Got it? lol

With the idea of using an interleaved palette you might be able to
design it such as the only places in your display that need to be
re-coloured only use a portion of the whole palette, and so need not
sacrifice a whole 128 colours. Like, if you only want shadows on floor
tiles and they only use 16 colours and you're sure that there is
no other colours beind drawn on, then you only need to spare 16
inbetween colours with which to use MAddMode.. or you could interleave
a second, or third set of colours also to provide different shadows,
lights, tints, depending on the MInk offset.

Aren't possibilities lovely :-)

The main other purpose of MAddMode, btw, is software colour cycling
without changing palette.... in your 256 colour game you don't wanna
have to spare colours which colourcycle and not be able to use them
elsewhere. MAddMode lets you cycle the pixels on the screen as if they
were colour cycling, albeit made easier if those colours are adjacent
in a single range, and remembering that as a colour disappears off the
top you might have to do an extra piece of code to change back to the
bottom (given that your range of cycle isnt 256 colours). (You can
also use MSimpleRemapMode to make software colourcycling a little
easier.)

Is there no end to the magic that mystress Mildred can manage? lol

