This kind of thing normally happens for one of a few reasons:

1) You've allocated some memory freed it and are trying to free it 
again or are trying to free memory that couldn't be allocated in the 
first place

2) You allocated some memory and used it for some Blitz object, (such 
as cludging a bitmap), and then left it up to Blitz to free the 
memory.

3) Your program somehow screws up the OS free memory list (either by 
problem 1 or writes to memory that ain't yours)

Are the 2000 and 4000 using the same OS?

What commands does it screw up on (even if it changes where it 
crashes, specific command names would be nice)?


