On 16-Feb-00, Tony Rolfe flashed:
>I'm going absolutely witless down here.    My motel manager program,
>which works fine on the A2000 is doing bizarre things on the A4000.

>There a number of things which do not cause enforcer hits themselves. 
>However, If I execute them then, later in the program, they cause a
>"Cannot Free Memory" error on some arbitrary command which has "Long
>Read from FFFFFFFF"  hits.  (Usually 2, sometimes only 1).    

>When that hit takes place, if I do not immediately Reboot, the cursor
>goes into VERY sticky mode, one hop  every 30 - 40 seconds (honest!!)
>and after about 5 minutes I get some arbitrary GURU.    When that
>occurs, the machine goes into an endless loop of flickering power LED
>followed by a bit of HD flicker, followed by power led etc.

>None of the problem code is unique (one particular file when all
>others seem OK, the ASL font requester when the file requester is OK).

>If it wasn't so code consistent, I'd suspect a hardware problem, but
>everything else in the system seems to work fine.    OK, the battery
>backed clock can't be found (flat battery I suspect) and the parallel
>port is doing a couple of wierd things, but all programs except
>the Motel Manager seem fine.

>Can anyone suggest ANYTHING I might try.    This program is vital to
>my business and I can't cut over to the 4K until it's fixed.



   Tony,

  I know quite a bit about A4000s as I not only have two of them myself
but have worked on numerous others.  The problems you describe may not
have anything to do with hardware, but there is a good possibility that
they do.  You are describing just the types of things which occure due
to power-pack brownout, CPU overheating and/or battery failure.  Either
one can cause funny and semingly unrelated errors, and brownout causes
just the type of slowdowns you describe.  These slowdowns often do not
occure with all software when the problem is borderline.  Software which
works the CPU (especially the mathco module) harder can cause the CPU to
overheat and slow down (sometimes so slow you can't tell it's going)
when it's nearly to that point allready.  Low power from the power pack
can also contribute to CPU overheating.  Other symptems of low power and/
or CPU overheating can be: unexplained Gurus, ports not working correctly,
unexpected errors on disk drives (especially floppy, but including all),
and unexpected glitches in software that normally works well.
  A dying or dead battery can also cause errors, and can DESTROY YOUR
MOTHERBOARD!!!.  Batterys leak acid in a vapour when they get old.

  The A4000s had/have chronic problems with the following:

- Leaky batterys destroying motherboard traces

- Weak powerpacks causing brownout

- Powerpack fans slowing down and/or stopping causing overheating of the
   powerpack (thus damaging it and causing brownout) and the CPU.

- CPU lacking heat-conductive grease between it and the heat sink.
   (this will definatly cause funny problems as the CPU will have only
   about 10-20% of the needed cooling)

- Airflow accross CPU and/or to the powerpack intake obstructed by cables
  or other obstruction (eg CD-ROM drive in the 5" bay to long).

- 5volt regulator near back of motherboard close to zorro backplane slot
  bad or going bad.



  All of the above can cause wierd problems such as those you mentioned.




  BATTERY

  I would open your case and check your battery WITHOUT DELAY.  Look for
solder turning strange colored and looking eroded, and look for light,
whitish smoke-like deposits spreading out on the MB from the battery
area from the acid fumes.  Don't procrastinate when a battery is going bad!
You WILL lose your motherboard.  If your battery has quit, GET IT OFF OF
THERE even if you can't see any signs of leakage.  You can unsolder it
(carefully so as to not overheat MB traces) if you have the knowledge,
or you can clip it off, leaving the mounts on the MB.  If you don't trust
your own abilitys get expert help.
  You can replace the battery with any battery OF THE SAME TYPE AND VOLTAGE.
Tandy/Radio Shack has many different cordless phone/cell phone batterys
which will work.  If your A4000 has a NiCad 3.5v battery (as most do) then
you are in luck.  There are many of these available which will all work.
Just choose one with a lead you can clip the connector off from and solder
the leads (pay close attention to matching + and - sides, check the
orientation of the old battery before removing it) to the MD connection
points or to the old battery's mounts if you left them there.  Be very
carefull not to overheat anything on the motherboard: get expert help if
your unsure.
  Do NOT use a lithium battery if your origional one was a NiCad as the
lithium one may EXPLODE!  This is because the lithium ones are not
rechargeable and the A4000 MB applies a charging current to the battery.
  Fasten the battery down in some fashion to prevent it from banging around
on your motherboard when you move the computer.





  CPU

  You can check (or have an expert check) the CPU for heat-conducting grease
between it and the heat sink by unclipping the spring-clip that holds the
heat sink to the CPU.  If the top of the CPU has no goop on it (is dry) then
yours was one of quite a few which some lazy bum on the production line
never bothered to put heat-conductive grease on.
  You can use heat-conductive grease purchased from Tandy or the local auto
parts store (used on ignition modules in many vehicles) to apply a thourough
film about .010"(U.S.) or .25mm thick on the top surface of the CPU before
clipping the heat sink back in place.  DO NOT apply it thick enough that it
will squish out the sides and ooze down onto the leads and traces, but put
enough on to make up for the irregularities in the planerity of the CPU and
the heat sink so that good conductivity of heat will occure over the entire
surfaces.  Get expert help with this if your are unsure what to do.



  POWER PACK

  Check the fan to see that it comes on immediatly with no hesitation or
slow run-up when the A4000 is powered on.  Also check to make sure that it
is blowing air out the back of the case and not sucking it in there as
some A4000s had their fans wired backwards which caused poor cooling.
  You can get a new fan that works perfectly from Tandy/Radio Shack for a
very reasonable price (about $15. U.S.).  I even re-lubed my origional fan
and got a couple of more years out of it, but it is MUCH easier to just
replace it.  DEFINATELY get expert help on this if your are unsure as the
fan is inside the power pack where there are DANGEROUS HIGH VOLTAGES!!!



  Voltage Regulator

  If your 5v regulator proves defective (and you will most likely need
expert help to determine this unless you have training in the field of
electronics) you can get a proper replacement for it at (wait for it!)
YOU GUESSED IT!... Tandy!  (Do these guys have everything or what!?)




Of course, any competant electronics supply house should also have the
above mentioned items as none of them are exactly rare like some of the
components of Amigas are.  On the battery, don't worry if they can't match
origional number.  Any battery of the same type and voltage will work as
long as it has at least as large of a capacity in mah as the origional
which shouldn't be a problem as all of the ones I have found have a much
larger capacity than the origional.  Just use the smallest one you can
find with the correct voltage and leads which can easily be adapted.




  OK, here goes the legal mumbo-jumbo.

  I take NO responcibility for anything you or anyone else does to yours or
anyones equiptment while attempting to follow the advice I have given.
It is up to you to see that you have the necessary skills and knowledge to
perform anything you do properly and safely, or to otherwise seek help from
an expert professional trained in the field.
  Be aware that electric and electronic equiptment is fragile and potentially
DANGEROUS, especially if you opt to remove the protective covering and mess
about inside.  You may do harm to yourself or your equiptment.




  Whatever you do, look after the battery, fan and heat sink situations as
all can do permanent damage to your computer, not to mention your data.



  Hope this is helpful.  I am posting it to the list because there are
probably others here who may have problems with these things either now or
in the future.





cach y'all later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)


