It needs adjusting in software. Modern monitors  have  a  helluva  lot
more hardware adjustments than any C= monitors, but you are stuck with
adjusting the monitor driver.

You might be using EGS with which I am not very  familiar.  I  suggest
using  either  CGX3  (or  4)  or P96. Don't believe the hype about P96
being a lot better--I use both and CGX has some advantages over P96. A
lot  of the speed benchmarking is quite bogus. Both CGX and P96 do all
screen adjustment on easy to use test screens. Just know which is  the
instant  cancel key, because you will lose sync when you adjust beyond
monitor capability. I never got CGX/CV64-3D 800x600 to fit  C=1960  at
35kHz  and settled for 720x576. I think the monitor needs to be driven
beyond 40kHz to get 800x600 to fit, and I wasn't game to do that.

> Also, I was planning to put the A4K into a tower with a Picasso IV
> board and an accellerator.    If the Spectrum will be good enough, I
> can use the PIV money to get a PPC accellerator, otherwise I'll be
> lucky if I can afford a 68060.     Any thoughts on that one?

In your situation I would stick with Spectrum and buy '060  (or  G4!).
Check  out  the  CGX  site and compare specs of various boards and you
will see the Spectrum is no pig. 1024 x 768 in 16  bit  is  lovely  if
ever  you get 17" monitor and Spectrum will drive that easily. I don't
feel the difference between Spectrum and P-IV  warrants  spending  the
money when you could have an '060 intead.

'060 and Spectrum together beats '040, P-IV AND four aces.

