Back, yup still there! :)  Whew!  Admiteddly the functions are still not
completed because I have been hard working on other things in the page
layout module (Platinum Publisher), and it'll be another few weeks before I
upload it to here and aminet.  Basically it's really simple.  There are two
libs; the HAM one will work on its own and the printer one requires the HAM
lib for colour remapping.  Admittedly the HAM lib remapping hasn't been
started but I have concentrated on one thing....

SPEED! :)  In the traditional guru fashion it bashes the metal in a kinda OS
friendly way; in that it first finds out where the planes are in memory
(using the OS BitMap structure) and then it starts bashing straigt into raw
memory by poking directly to the planes.

The HAM lib will have functions like:

* _PlotHAM{X,Y,Colour_Component,Value}_ - Plots a HAM 'ramp' at a certain
location specified by X and Y. R, G or B are defined in Colour_Component and
the intensity 0..15 in Value.

* _ReadHAM{X,Y,Colour_Component}_ - Reads the intensity of the specified
colour componet at position X,Y.

* _RemapHAM{SrcBitMap,DestBitMap_ID,Palette_ID}_ - Remaps a bitmap to a
specified destination BitMap which will use the base 16 colours specified by
Palette_ID.  The DestBitMap is a free BitMap's ID, it will produce a HAM-6
(6 plane OCS/ECS/AGA HAM) remapped bitmap which complies to the base
palette.  Extremely useful!

The printer library calls on the HAM lib but consists of currently one
simple function:

* _PrintBitMap{Width,Height,Density,Shade,*BitMap_Addr)_ - Basically Width and
Height are the sizes of the print outs in inches; regardless of the printer
or density (DPI) settings of the printer.  Density is 1-7 and depends on the
printer e.g.: a Epson Stylus Colour only uses 1-3, a Epson DM perhaps 1-7. 
1 is the worst and 7 is the best.  Shade is either black and white,
greyscale or colour; ignoring the ecentric Greyscale2 for the A2024.  The
Bitmap_Adr is a pointer to the BitMap you want to print.

/#  _*Note:_* that it is up to the user to make sure that the BitMap is 'large'#/
/#  enough to print at a high resolution; the function will print in strips#/
/#  depending on the size of the BitMap; if the BitMap is small but is to be#/
/#  printed at a large size; the print out quality will be poor.  Roughly#/
/#  200 pixels per inch of printout gives the best results since the HAM#/
/#  remapping limitations of the old 12BIT printer.device in AmigaOS 1.0-3.1#/
/#  , it means that though a picture will need to be enlarged with the OS#/
/#  function BitMapScale_() in order to make sure the remapping is as best as#/
/#  possible...  This will be fully documented in the docs.#/

