I also have had the same sort of problems using the Blitz-ReqTools library

It is definately the fault of the Blitz library, which was written for an
older version of ReqTools (I think) - in any case, it is buggy in regard to
filerequesters.

My solution is also to call ASL for filerequesters, through the OS commands
using a taglist, rather than the Blitz ASL library...

This way, if the user has ReqTools and is using the ReqTools patch, a
ReqTools file requester will appear, and everything works as it should.

And if they don't have ReqTools, an ASL filerequester will appear, and again
everything will work as it should...

The results either way are returned in the FileRequester structure
(NewType).

If anyone is interested, there is a full example on my website, on the Blitz
page, also in Aminet/dev/basic/

It says ASL-multi-select, but it can be used as normal one-file select as
well. (Or even as a real "Save" requester, where the user can create a new
drawer)

> 
>> 
>>> Also I have the requestor opening, and I'm able to
>> retrive the
>>> filename, but how do I get the Full path?

I don't have the docs for ReqTools library, but in ASL the results are
returned in:

*fr_File   ;pointer to a string with the name of the selected file
*fr_Drawer ;pointer to a string with the full path of the selected file

You can read these using something like:

drawer$ = peek.s(blah, blah...)

I'm sure the ReqTools filerequester structure has these in it as well, but
you'll have to look in the ReqTools docs for the correct structure
definition... 


> You might be able to use the Path$ (?) command (I
> can't remember what Blitz library that came under, I
> think it may have been Elmore's DOS lib) to get the
> path name.

There is a ProgPath$ (part of one of the RI libraries) which returns the
path of your own program.

