Ahh see we're breaking all the rules here, lol. 
 
> Someone said you used 040 optimised C2P code for the main
> engine..??? Would an 030 optimised version work any fast on an 030??

Someone might've said rightly that there is 040 code but that isn't
the whole story.

Depending on your choice of which cpu you have, like using the MCPU
command, or even better just letting it auto-detect your cpu (which
makes an internal call to MCPU), or was it Mc2pCPUmode (or did I scrap
that?).... anyway... by doing that you are telling the system what cpu
you have available and then when it comes time to make a call to Mc2p
it will check this and make a call to either an 040 or an 030
chunky-to-planar routine depending on the cpu. The 030 routine is
meant to work as best as possible on an 030 (or less) while the 040
routine is meant to work as best as possible on an 040 and also very
well on an 060. You may also find that if you use a c2pWindow which
does't have a line modulo... ie you are just c2p'ing the whole width
of the bitmap and it has no extra at the sides (ie gaps in memory), it
will do a faster non-modulo c2p routine which may gain a couple of
fps.

Mildred IS useable on an 030, like an 030/50, but it is simply a
question of how much stuff you can squeeze out of it. Typically the
results are that an 030/50 does half as much as an 040/25 and an
060/50 does twice as much.



