> snow and rain effects where very good. I however don't have the knowledge of
> how the commands worked, and how 68k works more to the point.
> 
> Any help? Paul? ;))

Hi Daniel,

The snow effect is really simple. Each snow pixel is has either X,Y
coords or an address in the buffer at which those X,Y coords are
located. There is then a baseX,baseY movement which is added to the
coordinate (or an address equivelent), and then a pair of randon
numbers Xvariance,Yvariance to make the movement path wiggle. You just
then need to check if the coords are outside of the buffer and if they
are you subtract the length or height of the buffer from the
coords/address so that it wraps back in at the top. Then actually
drawing the pixels is just your basic for-next affair going through an
array - 1 array of X,Y, 1 array of Xbase,Ybase, 1 array of
Xvary,Yvary. Precalculate the Xvary,Yvary randon numbers as its then
faster. You just then pull the numbers out from a different position
using an offset type thing. Treat the pixels like bobs... ie you gotta
keep track of the background and later restore it. So before you get
into the main loop you just randomize the X,Y coords throughout the
buffer. To do rain you just randomize like every fourth X,Y coord and
then adjust the remaining ones /based on/ that so that they will move
roughly in unison... which requires duplicating the data in the other
arrays too.


