Well it does, if chip mem access is limiting the speed, but of course
If the 8 plane copying is not slowed by the bus access, then droping
out planes is useless.

Of course it would be better to modify the c2p more so that the two last
planes are not converted, but it's not the main reason.
Because 060 would be fast enough to do the c2p for larger displays, but
the amount of data that the bus can carry through in certain amount of
time is so limited, that writeing to chip is limiting the size of the area.

This bus access bottle neck occurs, if you use larger displays like
maximum PAL overscan or the higher AGA modes. Same thing when dumping to
GFX boards, which are in zorro slots. That's why the PPC card GFX boards
can execute the doom etc ports faster! The bus of those B- and CVision
boards can put through 600 megs per second. So full frame copying for
60Hz 1280*1024 in 32 bpp isn't even near the limit of the bus, but zorro
and AGA buses can't do even half of it.

