Oh now I remember.
You just have to write new data to the sprite addressing on every line.
So do this: (don't know if this works like this)

Load the sprite position and data A and B registers for all 8 sprites
with the first lines pixel datas and positions ie 0-127.
Then wait the x position where the sprite 0 starts (this should be enough,
but you can sub 9 from the position if this does not work correctly).
Then write new data to the sprites data registers and new position as well

sprite 0 data A         ; Will reprecent pixels 0-15
sprite 0 data B
sprite 0 position

sprite 1 data A         ; Will reprecent pixels 16-31
sprite 1 data B
sprite 1 position

...

sprite 7 data A         ; Will reprecent pixels 112-127
sprite 7 data B
sprite 7 position


wait the correct position


sprite 0 data A         ; Will reprecent pixels 128-143
sprite 0 data B
sprite 0 position

sprite 1 data A         ; Will reprecent pixels 144-159
sprite 1 data B
sprite 1 position

...

sprite 7 data A         ; Will reprecent pixels 240-255
sprite 7 data B
sprite 7 position

sprite 0 data A         ; Will reprecent pixels 256-271
sprite 0 data B
sprite 0 position

sprite 1 data A         ; Will reprecent pixels 272-287
sprite 1 data B
sprite 1 position

...

sprite 3 data A         ; Will reprecent pixels 304-319
sprite 3 data B
sprite 3 position

And do it again for the next line and so on

You could also make here a Copper CPU interrupt and copy the datas for the
instructions above and use the second copperlist for this copy thing.
and the main list would just loop until it reaces certain point and would
exit rfom the loop. (reaced the bottom of display so no more GFX needing
copy.)

So NO WAITS in between, because copper move is 8 pixel wide.
(wait and skip are 9 pixel wide.)

multiplexing is another way of doing sprite graphics on screen, but it's
more limited, but needs only one sprite.

There you will write new data to one of the data registers and a new
position

